Study Information 
Hypotheses 
H*: when expected returns are constant, outcome variance will decrease an individual’s 
contributions toward a public good only when the distribution of possible outcomes includes 
the prospect of losses. 
 
Expected pattern of results: contributions will decrease when possible outcomes include losses. 
 
Design Plan 
Study type 
Experiment - A researcher randomly assigns treatments to study subjects, this includes field or 
lab experiments. This is also known as an intervention experiment and includes randomized 
controlled trials. 
Blinding 
No blinding is involved in this study. 
Is there any additional blinding in this study? 
Participants will not be informed about the study hypothesis. However, the independent 
variable (the possibility of loss prospects) will be manipulated within participant, which means 
that they will be aware of this manipulation. The study will run online, and experimenters will 
not interact directly with participants. 
Study design 

The study has a repeated measures design, with one independent variable (bonus variance) 
with 4 levels (none, low, medium, high). The variance level describes the possible bonus that 
participants will earn in each of 4 threshold games. 
No files selected 
Randomization 
Participants will be allocated to 4-person groups on a random basis. This will be achieved by the 
experimental software (OTree). The order in which participants will encounter the 4 games 
(each of which has a different bonus variance) will also be randomised. This will again be 
accomplished by the experimental software. 
Sampling Plan 
Existing Data 
Registration prior to creation of data 
Explanation of existing data 
No data 
Data collection procedures 
Adults will be recruited from the University of Exeter’s FEELE lab participant pool and / or the 
online survey platform Prolific to take part in a “Decision Making” study. This study will be 
conducted online using the OTree platform and the FEELE lab server at the University of Exeter. 
Participants will be paid GBP3 for completing the study and will have the opportunity of 
additionally earning a bonus that will depend on the decisions that they and other participants 
make in the study. We will recruit participants in batches of multiples of 4. Any participants who 
cannot be allocated to a group (e.g., because non-consents or dropouts reduce the numbers 
below a multiple of 4) will be paid a show-up fee of GBP1.50.  
 
In this study, participants will play a series of 4-person threshold public good games that 
manipulate the possibility of loss prospects in the outcome distribution of a public goods 
dilemma. Participants will first be introduced to the game. They will be told that they will play 
the game 4 times in total, and that each time they will be grouped with different people. At the 
start of each game they will receive 125 points that they have to split between a personal 
account and a shared account. They are able to keep points that they allocate to their personal 
account, but not those they allocate to the shared account. However, the shared account offers 
the possibility of a bonus. If the total number of points that the 4 group members contribute to 
the shared account meets or exceeds the threshold of 300 points, then a bonus will be divided 
equally among the 4 group members. If this threshold is not met, then there will be no bonus. 
Participants’ earnings for each game will be the sum of any points that remain in their personal 
account (if any) plus their share of the bonus (if any). They will be told about their earnings after 
they have played all 4 games (i.e., not after each game). At this point, one of these games will be 
randomly chosen and they will be paid out their earnings for this round at the rate of 1point = 

GBP0.01. Participants will then complete several comprehension questions to ensure that they 
understand the game and the basis for their final take home pay.  
 
At this point the study will start. Participants will be randomly allocated to groups of 4. To allow 
pre-play communication, participants will have the opportunity to spend 90-seconds 
exchanging free form chat when they are first allocated to their group at the start of each game. 
After the chat, they will be reminded about the decision that they need to make (splitting points 
between their personal account and the shared account) and informed about the bonus. After 
making their decision, participants will then be asked to indicate how much 6 different 
strategies played a role in their decision: “I think the other participants will not allocate points to 
the shared account and we will not get the bonus”, “I think other participants will allocate points 
to the shared account and I can benefit from the bonus without having to contribute”, “I don’t 
know what others are going to do and it’s not worth the risk of contributing to the shared 
account”, “I think the other participants will contribute to the shared account, so I want to 
contribute as well”, “I think contributing to the shared account is the right thing to do, 
regardless of what other participants decide”, and “I don’t know what others are going to do 
and it’s worth the risk of contributing to the shared account”. Participants will rate their 
strategies on 7-point Likert scales (1=not at all, 7=very much). Participants will also be asked to 
respond to a one-item measure of their fear of incurring a loss on a 7-point scale (1=not at all 
concerned, 7=very concerned): “If the bonus is provided, how concerned are you about 
incurring a loss”. Participants will then be allocated to a different group to play the second 
game, where this procedure will be repeated, and so on until they have finished the fourth 
game.  
 
In each game, the bonus will have a mean expected value of 600 points; however, the variance 
around this value will differ across games. Specifically, the no variance bonus will be worth a 
certain 600 points, the low variance bonus will be worth between 400 and 800 points, the 
medium variance bonus will be worth between 200 and 1000 points and the high variance 
bonus will be worth between 0 and 1200 points. Because the possible value of the latter two 
conditions are less than the threshold (of 300), these introduce the possibility of losses. Where 
there is variance in the bonus, the bonus information will be presented in the following form: 
“The bonus for this game is an amount randomly chosen between 400 and 800 points (all 
values equally likely to be chosen).” Participants will encounter each bonus once, and the order 
will be randomised across participant sessions. On completion of the study, participants will 
complete a short demographic survey.  
 
No files selected 
Sample size 

We will run a pilot analysis to inform the Monte Carlo simulations that our power analysis will 
be based on. Sample size will be finalised at that point, and we will re-register the study at that 
point. This pilot will recruit 20 participants in 5 groups to complete the study. Data on group 
and participant-level ICC and variance will be used to inform the monte carlo analysis (a draft of 
which can be seen in the related OSF page). 
Sample size rationale 
See above. Once the pilot study has been run, we will run Monte Carlo power analyses to 
determine sample size. 
Stopping rule 
For the study proper, in order to achieve the necessary sample size, we will continue 
recruitment until we have collected data from at least the specified number of individuals. As 
the precise number that will be recruited in a given session will vary for reasons out of our 
control (i.e., the number who sign up for a given session, the number who provide consent and 
the number who provide at least one response), it is possible that we will somewhat exceed our 
desired sample size. Because exclusions are based on participants’ contribution decisions 
(specifically, failing to respond to any of them) and these affect their payoffs, we will be able to 
track any excluded participants through the payment data. This means that we will not need to 
access the main datasheet.  
Variables 
Manipulated variables 
There is one manipulated variable: the variance of the bonus that will be shared among the 
4-person group playing the threshold public goods game. This has 4-levels: (1) no variance, 
where the bonus is a certain 600 points, (2) low variance, where the bonus will be worth 
between 400 and 800 points, (3) medium variance, where the bonus will be worth between 200 
and 1000 points and (4) high variance, where the bonus will be worth between 0 and 1200 
points. Importantly, the latter two conditions include the possibility of losses.  
 
Further details are provided above.  
 
No files selected 
Measured variables 
The primary DV is the number of points from their 125 point endowment that participants will 
allocate to the shared account.  
 
Participants will be asked to indicate the importance of different strategies in their decision 
making by rating the importance of 6 difference strategies on 7-point scales (1=not at all, 7=very 
much): 
“I chose to allocate the number of points that I did because:” 

-​
(fear of non-contribution) I think the other participants will not allocate points to the 
shared account and we will not get the bonus 
-​
(greed) I think other participants will allocate points to the shared account and I can 
benefit from the bonus without having to contribute 
-​
(loss aversion) I don’t know what others are going to do and it’s not worth the risk of 
contributing to the shared account 
-​
(no fear of non-contribution) I think the other participants will contribute to the shared 
account, so I want to contribute as well 
-​
(moral obligation) I think contributing to the shared account is the right thing to do, 
regardless of what other participants decide 
-​
(risk seeking) I don’t know what others are going to do and it’s worth the risk of 
contributing to the shared account 
 
Participants will also be asked to respond to a one-item measure of their fear of incurring a loss 
on a 7-point scale (1=not at all concerned, 7=very concerned): “If the bonus is provided, how 
concerned are you about incurring a loss?” 
 
Participants will be asked to complete a short demographic survey that will ask them about 
their gender (male, female, prefer to self describe, prefer not to say), age (in years) and country 
of residence.  
 
